Perform the following steps to remove specified parts (captions, footnotes, tables and figures) of TFL objects in the document. Under TFL > In-Text TFL, click ... at the bottom and select Batch Clear TFL Content from the menu. Choose the parts of the TFL objects you want to remove. Filter the TFL objects by selecting the relevant sections. Select the TFL objects on which you want to perform the action. Click Confirm.

Use the following steps to sync data on multiple TFLs in the document. note Data synchronization is restricted to specialized TFL objects within the document. Standard tables, figures, and listings cannot be modified or processed by the Create add-in. To enable data syncing, you must first Recognize TFLs and TFL Summaries to transform these elements into TFL objects. Under TFL > In-Text TFL, click Sync Data at the bottom. Select the sections in which you want to sync TFL data. Choose whether to sync TFL captions and footnotes. Click Sync. The sync process starts and may take a moment. Wait till the sync is complete and click Refresh to update the TFL sync status. The icons next to the TFLs denote different sync status. If you encounter any sync failures, proceed to Resolve Unsuccessful TFL Syncs. When synchronizing updated source data to the TFL in the document, you can choose to update the TFL summaries simultaneously. The triggered update tasks will be displayed in the AI Task Pane.

documents.t: You have the capability to remove multiple in-text TFLs simultaneously from your document by utilizing the TFL-section mapping table. Hereâ€™s how to proceed: Click Configure TFL located in the ribbon. To mark a TFL item for deletion, simply click the Delete icon situated on the right-hand side of the item. TFL items designated for removal will be highlighted in red and accompanied by a Cancel icon. Should you change your mind, clicking the Cancel icon will withdraw the deletion mark. Confirm your intention by clicking Confirm. The right-hand pane will now display the in-text TFLs marked for deletion. Access the menu at the bottom of this pane and choose Batch Delete TFLs. To view all in-text TFLs slated for deletion across all sections, select All Sections. Click Configure Content Generation. The complete outline of the document is displayed on the left, listing all the section headings extracted from the Word template. To configure how generative AI will auto-generate content for a section, either select the section heading in the outline inside the Template Design pane, or navigate to the section in the document, and click on this control: No rules configured, click to configure rules in the add-in. Generation method: Specify how you want the add-in to auto-generate content for the section based on the information source provided (in subsequent fields). Summarize Source Info (AIGC): The add-in will generate a lean summary of specified content in the source document using generative AI. Copy (Source): The add-in will copy the exact content verbatim from the specified content source into the section. Information Source: Provide related study document and specific sections in the document as the source information from which to generate content. There are two ways you can specify sections in a source reference document: Information Element (AI Extraction): The add-in will use generative AI to read the source document and automatically extract content based on your input. You don't have to enter the exact section heading name in the source document. Based on your input, the add-in will find the most relevant section or content element that best matches what you enter. Section Name Match: Provide the exact name of the section (case-insensitive) in the source document you want to use as source content. The add-in will look for sections in the source document that matches your input. Either way, if the source content you want to specify is not available in the drop-down list, just type its name in the search box and click the plus sign at the bottom to add it. Additional Prompt: If you opted to use AIGC in this section, you can provide additional prompt in to give detailed instructions to generative AI on how to generate content that meets your specific requirements. The prompt can be short and concise, or lengthy and detailed, depending on your documentation requirements. Here is an example of a short one: Use plain text with subtitle to describe but not bullet points. info You must click Save to save the configuration before moving to anther section; otherwise, all the changes you have made for the current section will be lost.

For effective incorporation of various TFL placeholders within your document, it's recommended that you set up a TFL-Section Mapping Table. To establish the TFL-section mapping table, select Configure TFL either from the Create Add-in ribbon or at the base of the TFL menu located in the right-hand pane. A TFL-section mapping table is structured with the following key columns. Section: Specifies the exact section number and section name within the document where the TFL will be inserted. In-Text TFL Name: The designated name for the TFL within the document. Source Data Caption/File Name: Here, you have the option to enter either the caption of the TFL as automatically recognized by the add-in or the name of the TFL source file (omitting the file extension like .rtf or .docx) that comprises the table, figure, or listing for insertion into the document. tip Given that TFL source files are typically prepared by statistical programmers or biostatisticians involved in your study, these files may not be immediately available at the initial stages of configuring the TFL-section mapping table for planning or drafting purposes. In such cases, this field can be left blank, allowing for later specification or automatic matching of the TFL source files once they become available. You can create the TFL-section mapping table in one of these two ways: Manually Maintain the TFL-Section Mapping Table Maintain the TFL-Section Mapping Table Using the TFL Config File

documents.t: The Create add-in offers tools for integrating Tables, Figures, and Listings (TFLs) into Microsoft Word documents as specialized TFL objects. documents.t: Integrating variables into your document offers a streamlined approach to managing recurrent pieces of information, such as the name of a test drug or its usual route of administration. By defining these repeating elements as variables, you can insert the relevant variable wherever needed within the document. This method centralizes updates; changing the information in one place automatically reflects across all instances where the variable is used. Utilizing variables enhances the uniformity, standardization, and structure of your documentâ€™s wording. After signing in to Create on the AuroraPrime platform, follow these steps to create a preliminary draft of protocol synopsis. Under Protocol Synopsis, click Create. Enter key study information and click Create. Click Edit to begin entering the detailed study design information needed to generate the draft protocol synopsis. You can save your changes at any time and return later to complete all the fields. For some study design information, the system provides similar trials for your reference. Click Reference for similar trials to display a list of trials relevant to the current study. Filter reference trials by variables such as age, sex, and disease conditions. Click a trial link to view its details, which will open in a new tab on the source site. To gain a holistic view of all the reference trials and insights into the protocol design, click In-Depth Analysis to open Protocol Design in a new tab. Under this menu, you can explore all collected reference trials through data analysis and visualization, and drill down into specific studies derived from authoritative sources. After completing all the detailed study information, click Save. The system will automatically generate a draft protocol synopsis from the provided information in the background. Click Download Synopsis to download a preliminary draft of the protocol synopsis in Word format. You can open the draft synopsis in Microsoft Word to edit and finalize the document.

documents.t: After signing in to Create on the AuroraPrime platform, follow these steps to create a preliminary draft of a specified document type. Under Document Writing, click Generate Document and select the desired document type. Enter the key study information required to generate the draft document. Explanation of some fields: Document ID: Enter a string that uniquely identifies the document, following your organization's naming conventions for the specified document type. For example, for a study protocol, the document ID can be the study ID. Document Structure Template: Choose a template that defines the document structure, specifying which sections to include and how the content is derived from associated documents. The structure templates are predefined in the Content Template Library by the study admin. Contact your study admin for details. Associated Documents: If the selected structure template requires content to be derived from associated documents, specify the required documents either by uploading them or selecting them from already uploaded documents. It may take a moment for the system to parse an uploaded document in the background. You can proceed to enter the remaining information, but you won't be able to generate the draft document until all associated documents are fully processed. Enter any additional optional information based on your protocol design. Click Confirm to save the changes. The summary information of the document is displayed in the document list with the status "Not Started." Click Generate Draft. The document status will change to "In Progress." Please allow some time for the system to generate the draft document in the background. You may need to refresh the page to view the updated status. When the drafting process is complete, click the Download icon to download the generated draft document. Please note that the document at this stage is a shell or skeleton containing only the outline. It must be fleshed out using the Prime Create add-In. Open the downloaded document in Microsoft Word. From the AuroraPrime Create menu, click Start Create. In the Auro-Complete dialog box, click Confirm to proceed. Section by section, the Create Add-In automatically populates AI-generated content into the document. Wait until all sections are populated with content, then save the completed draft document. note The AI-generated document serves as a preliminary draft and provides a solid starting point for further editing and finalization using the Prime Create add-in's features. For the Clinical Study Report (CSR), you can proceed to incorporate TFLs (Tables, Figures, and Listings) and TFL Summaries into the document as needed.

An abbreviations table in a clinical document is a dedicated section or list that explains the meanings of abbreviations, acronyms, and symbols used throughout the document. Use the following steps to auto-generate an abbreviations table for your document. In the document, place the cursor where you want to insert the abbreviations table. Click Edit Abbreviation List. The system recognizes all potential abbreviations from the document and display them in a list. You can further filter and hand-pick the ones you want to include in the abbreviation table. A. Narrow down the abbreviations list by the minimum times they must appear in the document. B. Select a generation method Ignore in-text list of abbreviations A new list of abbreviations will be generated without factor in any existing list of abbreviations in the document. Compare with in-text list of abbreviations New abbreviations will be merged with any existing list of abbreviations in the document based on the set filter criteria. C. Whether or not to include abbreviations present in TFLs and TFL footnotes. D. Sort the list by either name. E. Sort the list by either occurrence. F. It's common for an abbreviation to stand for multiple meanings depending on its context. If any abbreviation is not interpreted accurately, select from a list of possible meanings the correct one in your document. G. To exclude an abbreviation from your document, switch it off. Under the Abbreviation Style tab, you can specify the format and sorting method of the abbreviations in the table. Click Submit and Insert into Text to insert the abbreviation table into the document. Please note the following: If there are already abbreviations in the table, you can add, delete or integrate the existing content when editing it again. Identify the following two abbreviation formats of TFL in the document: Abbreviation, Abbreviation Name; Abbreviation, Abbreviation Name; Abbreviation=Abbreviation Name, Abbreviation=Abbreviation Name,

documents.t: Seamlessly integrated with Microsoft Word 365, AuroraPrime Create Add-In is a purpose-built extension designed to elevate the creation of clinical documentation. Tailored specifically for crafting essential clinical documentation like clinical study reports (CSRs) and study protocols, this add-in serves as a powerful tool for medical writers to produce high quality documentation in an efficient manner.
Here is a high-level overview of the Prime create authoring workflow:
After you have completed configuring a document template, you must publish it to the AuroraPrime Create Content Library before it can be used by medical writers in the organization.

The Create add-in offers tools for integrating Tables, Figures, and Listings (TFLs) into Microsoft Word documents as specialized TFL objects. These objects allow for direct manipulation and processing by the add-in. However, TFLs that are manually inserted via Word's Insert menu or through third-party tools will initially be regular tables, figures, and listings. These need to be identified and transformed into TFL objects to be compatible with the Create add-in's functionalities. Similarly, any standard text segments serving as summaries for TFLs must also be detected and converted into TFL summary objects. This conversion is essential for the Create add-in to effectively parse and manipulate these elements within the document.

Integrating variables into your document offers a streamlined approach to managing recurrent pieces of information, such as the name of a test drug or its usual route of administration. By defining these repeating elements as variables, you can insert the relevant variable wherever needed within the document. This method centralizes updates; changing the information in one place automatically reflects across all instances where the variable is used. Utilizing variables enhances the uniformity, standardization, and structure of your documentâ€™s wording. This not only significantly reduces the time spent on manually updating repeated information but also minimizes the risk of human errors in editing. Such a strategy is particularly beneficial in documents requiring frequent updates or containing complex, repetitive data, ensuring both efficiency and consistency in document preparation.

When you sign in to AuroraPrime Create after creating a new document or open one for the first time, you will encounter Document Initialization Settings screen. Here, you are prompted to enter essential information about the document you are working on. The add-in will remember these settings, ensuring that they are automatically applied to the document in subsequent sessions. note The Prime Create add-in only supports .docx documents. Document Purpose: For the writer role, Document Writing is the only available option. Associated Study: The specific study for which the document is being created. Document Type: The category of the document, such as CSR or Protocol. Document Language: The language in which the document is written (not the add-in UI language). The Create add-in will generate AI-produced content in the chosen language. Import from Template: If you choose Yes, you will be prompted to select a pre-configured document template (if available). After confirming the settings, a new document will be created based on the selected template.

After TFLs have been uploaded, you can insert them directly from source into the document. In the document, navigate to the appropriate section and place the cursor where you want to insert the TFL. In the add-in pane, under TFL Source, navigate to the TFL source file. You can use click Search and type the file name to quickly locate it in the list. Optionally, click Preview to make sure you are selecting the the correct TFL for insertion. Click Insert into Doc to insert the TFL into the cursor position in the document. If the page width of a TFL source file (RTF format) exceeds a certain length, the system will automatically switch the corresponding page in the document where the TFL is inserted to landscape orientation.

Contact your Microsoft 365 admin for more information. Apart from having the Prime Create add-in installed in your Microsoft Word through central deployment in your organization, you can also manually install Prime Create from the Office Add-Ins Store using a straightforward process. Open Microsoft Word 365: Launch your Word application. Navigate to the Home Tab: Click on the Home tab in the top menu bar. Choose Add-Ins: Click on the Add-Ins option and choose More Add-ins. Click on it. This will direct you to the Office Add-Ins Store. Search for the Add-In: Use the search bar to find AuroraPrime Create. Select and Install: Click on Add to initiate the installation process. Follow Prompts and Permissions: Follow the on-screen prompts to complete the installation. Access the Add-In: Once installed, Prime Create add-in appears as a new ribbon within the Word interface, giving you easy access to the added functionalities.

Published templates are managed in the AuraPrime Create Content Library. Sign into the AuroraPrime platform and navigate to the Create Content Management menu. Select a document type in the left pane to view a list of draft and published templates of that type. Click a template to preview the template online and view its configuration details. To make changes to a template, you must Modify a Published Template in Microsoft Word using the Create add-in. Click the Download action icon to download the template in Microsoft Word format. Click the Delete icon to delete the template permanently from the library. Only draft templates can be deleted.

documents.t: In the TFL-section mapping table, you can manually maintain mappings between TFLs and document sections, one row for each TFL. Click Add Row at the bottom to create new section-TFL mappings, one row for each TFL item. For each row, specify a section in the current document and enter the name of the TFL. Recognize Conclusion and Associated TFL Select this option if you want to primarily identify regular text as TFL summary objects and link them with corresponding TFL objects in the document. Select the sections in the document to scan for candidate items to be converted into TFL objects and TFL summary objects. The system displays all the tables and figures in the selected sections as potential candidates for conversion into TFL objects, along with accompanying text for TFL summaries. tip Recognizing TFL and Summary can only associate a piece of TFL summary text with a single TFL object. To associate a piece of TFL summary text with multiple TFL objects, use the Convert Text to TFL Summary feature. Review and select the items you want to convert into TFL objects and TFL summary objects. Click Confirm to perform the conversion. TFL objects can be viewed under the In-Text TFL tab; TFL summary objects can be viewed under the TFL Summary tab. tip In a Word document, a specialized TFL object is easily identifiable: it is highlighted in grey when you hover your cursor over it. To select a TFL object, simply click on its control handle, which is located in the upper left corner of the object.

The Create add-in offers tools for integrating Tables, Figures, and Listings (TFLs) into Microsoft Word documents as specialized TFL objects. These objects allow for direct manipulation and processing by the add-in. These need to be identified and transformed into TFL objects to be compatible with the Create add-in's functionalities. Integrating variables into your document offers a streamlined approach to managing recurrent pieces of information, such as the name of a test drug or its usual route of administration. By defining these repeating elements as variables, you can insert the relevant variable wherever needed within the document. This method centralizes updates; changing the information in one place automatically reflects across all instances where the variable is used. Utilizing variables enhances the uniformity, standardization, and structure of your documentâ€™s wording. This not only significantly reduces the time spent on manually updating repeated information but also minimizes the risk of human errors in editing. Such a strategy is particularly beneficial in documents requiring frequent updates or containing complex, repetitive data, ensuring both efficiency and consistency in document preparation.
